SIMPLE: pyramidal
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pyramidal
<hw>Py*ram`i*dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>pyramidal</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to a pyramid; in the form of a a
pyramid; pyramidical; <as>as, <ex>pyramidal</ex>
cleavage</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mystic obelisks stand up⟦br⟧
Triangular, <qex>pyramidal</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Mrs.
Browning.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1169 --></p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Crystallog.)</fld> <def>Same as
<er>Tetragonal</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pyramidal numbers</b></col> <fld>(Math.)</fld>,
<cd>certain series of figurate numbers expressing the number of balls or
points that may be arranged in the form of pyramids. Thus 1, 4, 10, 20,
35, etc., are <xex>triangular pyramidal numbers</xex>; and 1, 5, 14, 30,
55, etc., are <xex>square pyramidal numbers</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyramidal</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pyramidal
<hw>Py*ram"i*dal</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<def>One of the carpal bones. See <er>Cuneiform</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2
<sd>(b)</sd>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pyramidally</ent>⟦br⟧
